    <h2>Transmission of Viral Gastroenteritis</h2><br><br>
    <p>Viral gastroenteritis is typically transmitted through close contact, shared food or drink, and contaminated surfaces.</p>
    <br><br>
    <h2>Symptoms of Rotavirus Infection</h2><br><br>
    <p>Watery Diarrhea: Lasts for three to eight days.<br>
        Vomiting: Usually occurs at the onset of illness and may last up to three days.<br>
        Fever: A mild-to-moderate fever often accompanies other symptoms during a rotavirus infection.<br>
        Abdominal Pain: Some individuals may experience stomach cramps or discomfort due to inflammation in the small intestine caused by the virus.</p>
        <br><br>
    <h2>Preventive Measures for Reducing Risk</h2><br><br>
    <p>To reduce your risk of contracting viral gastroenteritis, ensure frequent handwashing with soap and warm water, maintain a distance from infected persons, and clean surfaces regularly. Also, make sure you are up-to-date on your rotavirus vaccination as it is an effective way to prevent infection.</p>

